Explaining functions by graphical representation and notation

Look at the graph of y = 2x + 1 on the right. The relation between the value of 1 on the x-axis and the value of 3 on the y-axis can be written as 1→ 3. This indicates that 1 is the first  element and 3 is the last element.

In this case, we can say that 1 is mapped to 3. Similar 8 to 3 → 7, 5 → 11 and so on. Every point (x, y) on the line is 6 corresponding to the mapping of x → y where x on the x-axis is 4 mapped to y on the y-axis.

The relation from part of the mapping x → y can be represented by an arrow diagram as shown below.

Thus, this type of relation is known as function or mapping. In general:

Function relating set X to set Y is a special relation where each element x
X is mapped to one and only one element y
